# Convex Validator Patterns

## Reusable Validators

Per [Convex Stack: Keep validators from going stale](https://stack.convex.dev/types-cookbook#keep-validators-from-going-stale), export field objects from `schema.ts` to maintain consistency:

### Export Field Objects

```ts
// convex/schema.ts
export const statusType = v.union(
  v.literal('approved'),
  v.literal('archived'),
  v.literal('backlog'),
  v.literal('published'),
);

export const timestampFields = {
  createdAt: v.optional(v.number()),
  deletedAt: v.optional(v.number()),
  updatedAt: v.optional(v.number()),
};

// Export field objects (without system fields)
export const itemFields = {
  ...timestampFields,
  description: v.optional(v.string()),
  status: statusType,
  title: v.string(),
};

// Use in schema
export default defineSchema({
  items: defineTable(itemFields).index('by_status', ['status']),
});
```

### Use for Return Validators

Wrap field objects with `v.object()` for return validators:

```ts
// convex/items.ts
import { itemFields } from './schema';

export const list = query({
  args: {},
  returns: v.array(v.object(itemFields)), // ✅ Reuses schema fields
  handler: async (ctx) => {
    return await ctx.db.query('items').collect();
  },
});

// ❌ Don't use v.any() for simple queries
returns: v.array(v.any())
```

### Mutation Args: Use Subsets

For mutations, define args separately (often a subset of fields):

```ts
export const create = mutation({
  args: {
    // Only user-provided fields (no auto-generated timestamps/slugs)
    description: v.optional(v.string()),
    status: v.optional(statusType), // ✅ Reuse common validators
    title: v.string(),
  },
  // ...
});
```

### Composite Return Types

For queries that join multiple tables, use `v.any()` with TypeScript comments:

```ts
returns: v.union(
  v.object({
    item: v.any(), // Doc<"items">
    owner: v.union(v.any(), v.null()), // Doc<"users"> | null
  }),
  v.null(),
)
```

**Why:** Field objects keep schema and validators in sync. Changes propagate automatically.

## Index Optimization

### Redundant Indexes

Compound indexes can be used for prefix queries - remove redundant single-field indexes:

```ts
// ✅ Optimal
.index('by_user_and_category', ['userId', 'categoryId'])

// ❌ Redundant (already covered by compound index above)
.index('by_user', ['userId'])
```

Use compound index for both queries:
```ts
// Query by prefix only
.withIndex('by_user_and_category', (q) => q.eq('userId', id))

// Query by full compound
.withIndex('by_user_and_category', (q) => q.eq('userId', id).eq('categoryId', catId))
```

**Exception:** Keep both only if you need different sort orders.

### Schema Audit Checklist

1. Remove indexes that are prefixes of compound indexes
2. Remove unused indexes
3. Add indexes for filtered fields with large result sets (1000+)
4. Use pagination/`.take()` instead of `.collect()` for large queries
